      "SummaryText": "actors.\n\nEach of the elements listed above are documented and routinely reviewed for improvement.\n\n\nFive-Year Accident History [68.155(d)]\n\nNone in the last 5 years\n\n\nEmergency Response Program [68.155(e)]\n\nThe BG Chlor-Alkali-VCM facility has established a written emergency response plan and maintains an emergency response team (ERT) trained in these emergency response procedures.  All plant personnel are trained in evacuation procedures and in-plant drills are conducted periodically.  The drills are used to test the response time of the Emergency Response Team, to test the plant employee accountability program, and to activate the plant's Emergency Command Center (ECC).  In addition, the BG Chlor-Alkali-VCM facility has developed a Special Situations Plan (SSP) which is a program designed for responding to emergencies that may have impacts beyond the immediate plant and is a supplement to the Emergency Response Plan.  \n\nThe facility is a member of the La Porte Local Emergency Planning Committee (LEPC), which includes industrial and public entities.\n\n\nPlanned Changes to Improve Safety [68.155(f)]\n\nThe BG Chlor-Alkali-VCM facility constantly tries to improve the safety of the processes through annual reviews of our plant procedures, near misses and incident investigation programs, and a program soliciting safety and environmental suggestions from the plant employees.  Specific changes include installation of additional process controls and enhancements on the railcar unloading system and on the sphere level monitoring system."
    },
    {
      "ESSeqNum": 0,
      "FacilityID": 1000113158,
      "SummaryText": "Occidental Chemical Corporation\nBG Chlor-Alkali VCM Facility at La Porte, Texas\n\nExecutive Summary\n\nAccidental Release Prevention and Emergency Response Policies [68.155(a)]\n\nOccidental Chemical has established a system for the safe operation of the process at this facility that includes the prevention of accidental releases of hazardous substances.  One component of this system is a program to manage the risks of accidental releases at the BG Chlor-Alkali-VCM facility.  This program conforms to the requirements of the Environmental Protection Agency's regulation 40 CFR part 68, Accidental Release Prevention Requirement Risk Management Programs (the RMP rule) and the requirements of OSHA 1910.119.  This document is intended to satisfy the RMP plan requirement of the RMP rule and to provide the public with a description of the risk management program at the BG Chlor-Alkali-VCM facility.\n\n\nStationary Source and Regulated Substances Handled [68.155(b)]\n\nThe BG Chlor-Alkali-VCM facility consists of two chemical production plants that are both owned by Occidental Chemical Corporation:  Battleground Chlor-Alkali Plant and La Porte VCM Plant. These two plants are located on contiguous property and the operations are within the same industrial group.  Therefore, these two chemical plants are considered one stationary source with two processes\n.\nThe facility handles six substances and one mixture that are regulated by the RMP rule.\n\n\nGeneral Accidental Release Prevention Program and Prevention Steps [68.155(c)]\n\nThe BG Chlor-Alkali-VCM facility's prevention program has been prepared so that it conforms to both the OSHA Process Safety Management and the EPA Risk Management Program regulations.  The program consists of the following elements:\n\nProcess Safety Information, Process Hazard Analysis, Operating Procedures, Training, Mechanical Integrity, Management of Change, Pre-Startup Review, Compliance Audits, Incident Investigation, Employee Participation, Key Procedures, Contr"
    }
